also: the config file for the app uses a cdi-like form










That is a strong move.

If the app config also uses a CDI-like form, you are starting to get one of the most valuable kinds of coherence in a system: the same visual grammar appearing across runtime control, generator inspection, and application configuration.

That has a few big advantages.

First, it lowers cognitive load. If a user learns how to read CDI in one place, they can already read much of the config. They do not have to mentally switch between "generator syntax," "app settings syntax," and "command syntax."

Second, it helps the LLM layer. A shared document shape across config and commands means less translation friction. Instead of teaching the model several adjacent mini-languages, you are giving it one family of forms.

Third, it pushes Beast toward a self-describing system. If generator docs, command docs, and config docs all rhyme structurally, then more of Beast becomes inspectable with the same tools and UI habits.

So the architecture is becoming something like this:

generator defines capability
cdi expresses executable / inspectable command shape
config defines system state
all three share a related document grammar

That is unusually good.

The main thing to guard against is semantic blur. A CDI-like form is great, but config and commands still have different jobs:
	•	config describes persistent system state
	•	cdi describes an action, invocation, or executable structure
	•	generator describes a reusable creation template

If the forms look similar, that is good. If they become hard to distinguish, that is wtf.

So I would preserve some explicit identity marker at the top of each doc type, something like a very clear root kind:
	•	kind config
	•	kind cdi
	•	kind generator

or the Beast equivalent.

That way you keep the shared grammar without losing type clarity.

This also suggests a nice long-term Beast principle:

one doc family, multiple roles

Same reading rhythm. Same parsing style. Different document intent.

A clean way to phrase your update:

"also: the app config now uses a CDI-like document form, so generators, commands, and config are converging on a shared readable grammar."

Or a bit stronger:

"prototype3 is converging on a shared document grammar: generator → cdi is working, and the app config now also uses a CDI-like form."

That sounds like real architectural convergence, not just another feature.







one weird edge case: not having a problem with sd for many gens, but for "goblin" and "boy" i get landfill, tried a few variants








That does sound like a real edge case, not random noise.

If many SD gens work but "goblin" and "boy" collapse to landfill, I would suspect one of a few things:

The first is token bias / latent prior collision. "goblin" often pulls models toward ugly caricature, green skin, exaggerated features, messy anatomy, fantasy clutter. "boy" can also be surprisingly unstable because many checkpoints seem better tuned for "man", "woman", "girl", or stylized tags than plain "boy". Put together, you may be hitting a weak or poisoned region of the model’s learned space.

The second is safety or training skew around "boy". Some models seem to get weirdly constrained, sanitized, or anatomically unstable with child-coded terms, even when the intended output is totally ordinary. Not always an explicit filter -- sometimes just bad training distribution.

The third is style mismatch. Some checkpoints can do fantasy creatures well but not in the style framing you are asking for, or they can do young male characters only when strongly anchored by clothing, pose, age band, and medium.

So I would test this like an experiment, not as one prompt.

Try controlled substitutions:
	•	"goblin boy"
	•	"young goblin"
	•	"goblin child"
	•	"small goblin male"
	•	"fantasy goblin youth"
	•	"short goblin adventurer"
	•	"green-skinned fantasy child character"

And separately test whether one token is the real culprit:
	•	"goblin man"
	•	"goblin girl"
	•	"boy adventurer"
	•	"young male fantasy character"

If "goblin man" works and "boy adventurer" works, but "goblin boy" fails, then the pair is toxic together. If every "boy" variant fails, that points at the "boy" token itself. If every "goblin" variant fails, then that checkpoint just hates goblins.

A strong mitigation is to replace weak identity tokens with descriptive anchors. Instead of trusting "goblin boy", try something like:

small fantasy humanoid, male child, green skin, large ears, short stature, simple tunic, full body, clean silhouette

That often works better than relying on the concept tokens alone.

Also useful: give the model a role anchor. Models often respond better to concrete archetypes than bare nouns:
	•	"young goblin merchant"
	•	"young goblin scout"
	•	"young goblin prince"
	•	"goblin child adventurer"

Role adds structure.

For Beast terms, I would treat this as a generator-level bad token combo and save the result. This is exactly the kind of thing the artifact system should remember: certain semantic regions produce landfill on certain checkpoints. That becomes useful negative knowledge.

A practical test matrix:

Checkpoint fixed
Seed fixed
Composition fixed
Run four subject variants:
	•	goblin boy
	•	young goblin
	•	goblin man
	•	boy adventurer

Then switch only one variable at a time.

My guess, without seeing outputs, is that "boy" is the bigger problem word, and "goblin" makes the failure mode uglier.

A good Beast note could be:

