with empty prompts or weak keywords in testing, id almost always get a city/town outdoor view, thoughts?






Yes -- that is a meaningful signal.

If empty prompts or very weak keywords usually collapse toward a city or town outdoor view, that suggests your checkpoint has a strong default visual prior. In plain terms: when the conditioning is weak, the model falls back to the most statistically comfortable scene it knows how to make.

And a city / town exterior is a very plausible fallback because it is:
	•	common in training data
	•	compositionally easy
	•	rich in mid-scale structure
	•	visually "complete" without needing a strong subject
	•	safe for the model when it is underconstrained

So I would read this as:

weak prompt → model prior dominates → default scene template appears

That also helps explain your goblin/boy issue. If the model has weak or conflicting grounding for a subject, it may partially "give up" on the intended character and drift back toward its comfortable default scene manifold.

A few useful interpretations:

1. your checkpoint is scene-biased by default
Not neutral. Not blank-canvas. It wants to paint "a plausible image," and its center of gravity seems to be outdoor built environments.

2. empty prompt behavior is a diagnostic
This is actually a good test. It tells you what the model "dreams about" when left alone. That default is part of the checkpoint’s personality.

3. weak nouns may be getting overpowered
If "goblin" or "boy" is not strongly anchoring composition, the model may be blending:
	•	weak subject token
	•	strong scene prior
	•	generic image-quality priors

Result: landfill, drift, bad composition, or irrelevant outdoor scene.

What I would do next is formalize this as a checkpoint profiling test.

Test a fixed matrix:
	•	empty prompt
	•	one weak noun
	•	one strong archetype
	•	one explicit composition
	•	one explicit subject + composition
	•	one explicit subject + blank background

For example:
	•	""
	•	boy
	•	wizard
	•	a person standing
	•	young goblin standing facing camera
	•	young goblin standing facing camera on a plain gray background

That lets you see where the model stops free-falling into town-view mode.

My expectation:
	•	weak prompt: town/city
	•	vague subject: subject+scene drift
	•	strong archetype: better subject lock
	•	explicit composition/background: much more stable

This also suggests a practical Beast rule:

some checkpoints need anti-default anchoring

Meaning: if the model defaults to outdoor scene clutter, your generator should explicitly fight that with:
	•	plain background
	•	full body in frame
	•	centered subject
	•	no environment
	•	character sheet / concept art / sprite sheet style
	•	isolated subject

So instead of:
goblin boy

you may need something more like:
young goblin character, full body, centered in frame, plain background, isolated subject, character design sheet

That is not just "better prompting." It is compensating for checkpoint bias.

I would absolutely save this as checkpoint metadata or a Beast note. Something like:

default weak-prompt prior: town outdoor scene

That is valuable generator knowledge.

A compact phrasing:

